  "prompt": "How do I help someone cope with the death of a parent?",
  "response": "Helping someone cope with the loss of a parent can be challenging. Here are some supportive ways to help:\n\n1. Be present and listen\n- Allow them to talk about their feelings\n- Don't try to \"fix\" their grief\n- Validate their emotions\n\n2. Offer practical support\n- Help with daily tasks\n- Assist with funeral arrangements\n- Provide meals or run errands\n\n3. Avoid clich\u00e9s\n- Don't say things like \"they're in a better place\"\n- Don't tell them how to feel\n- Acknowledge their pain sincerely\n\n4. Check in regularly\n- Grief doesn't end quickly\n- Continue to offer support weeks and months later\n- Send texts, make calls, visit occasionally\n\n5. Respect their grieving process\n- Everyone grieves differently\n- Don't set expectations for how they should feel\n- Be patient and understanding\n\n6. Suggest professional help if needed\n- Recommend grief counseling\n- Offer to help find support groups\n- Assist in finding mental health resources\n\n7. Remember important dates\n- Acknowledge birthdays and anniversaries\n- Send a card or make a kind gesture\n- Show you haven't forgotten their loss\n\n8. Encourage self-care\n- Help them maintain healthy habits\n- Suggest gentle exercise or activities\n- Support their emotional and physical well-being",
